               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17960113-91-person980">
                  JONATHAN
                   MURRAY
               <interp inst="t17960113-91-person980" type="surname" value="MURRAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person980" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person980" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a pawnbroker, in East Smithfield; the prisoner pledged a watch with me. Q. Did he speak English when he pledged it? - A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17960113-91-person981">
                  JUAN
                   CHEVRIER
               <interp inst="t17960113-91-person981" type="surname" value="CHEVRIER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person981" type="given" value="JUAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person981" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a foreigner; I lodged on the 4th of January in the house of Joseph Gomez; it is No. 4; I don't know the name of the street.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know where the prisoner lived? - A. Yes; in the same house; I lost my watch on the 4th of January; I had left it locked up in my chest about twelve o'clock at noon; when I returned at seven in the evening, I missed it.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know who took it out of your chest? - A. Yes; the prisoner at the bar; it was a silver watch, and the chain a metal one; the prisoner with his own key opened it.</p>
               <p>Q. Are you sure you did not give or lend him the watch? - A. No; I left it locked up in the chest.</p>
               <p>Murray. On Monday the 24th of January, about four or five o'clock in the afternoon, 
               <persName id="t17960113-91-person982">
                  Paulo
                   Offracius
               <interp inst="t17960113-91-person982" type="surname" value="Offracius"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person982" type="given" value="Paulo"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person982" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , the prisoner, pawned a silver watch, for two guineas, which the prosecutor has got.</p>
               <p>Q. How did you make him understand? - A. A few days before, he came with a countryman of his to pawn a pair of knee buckles; he understood English; and when he came to take out the knee-buckles, be pledged this watch; he asked three guineas and an half for it; he pledged it in the name of John Fracius; he could understand money in English; and he said, if I would give him the paper, he would come again for it; by order of the Magistrates, I gave it to the prosecutor; the maker of it lives but a few doors from us, Mr. Jackson, a man that frequently serves foreigners with watches.(The watch was produced in Court.)</p>
               <p>Q. To Chevrier. Are you sure that is your property? - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>Murray. This is the watch I took in pledge from the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17960113-91-person983">
                  ELIZABETH
                   GOMEZ
               <interp inst="t17960113-91-person983" type="surname" value="GOMEZ"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person983" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person983" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t17960113-91-person984">
                  Joseph
                   Gomez
               <interp inst="t17960113-91-person984" type="surname" value="Gomez"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person984" type="given" value="Joseph"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person984" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; the prosecutor and prisoner both lodged with me: On Monday the 4th of January, the prosecutor came home about seven in the evening; he went up to his chest, and came down, and said he had lost his watch; my mother and I went to a great many pawnbrokers, and found the watch at Mr. Murray's.</p>
               <p>Q. Had you no conversation with the prisoner? A. None at all.</p>
               <p>Q. What is your mother's name? - A. Ann Evans.</p>
               <p>Murray. Mr. Beare came to enquire after the watch about seven in the evening; and about eight o'clock this young woman and her mother came upon the same business.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17960113-91-person985">
                  JOSEPH
                   BEARE
               <interp inst="t17960113-91-person985" type="surname" value="BEARE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person985" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-person985" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I apprehended the prisoner; the prosecutor came to my house, and said he had been robbed of his watch; that is all I know of it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's defence. I pawned the watch with the prosecutor's leave; I had lent him two guineas; I asked him for the two guineas; he said he had not two guineas; I said, if he had not got it, I was in want of money, and he said pawn the watch; the prosecutor's chest was open, and he told me I might take it out.</p>
               <p>Q. (To Chevrier.) Did you owe the prisoner two guineas? - A. I never knew him in my life.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you owe him two guineas? - A. Not a farthing.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you give him leave to pawn your watch? - A. No.</p>
               <p>Q. (To Mrs. Gomez.) How long have you known the prisoner? - A. About three weeks.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know any thing of his character at all? - A. No; I have known the prosecutor about three months.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know of any transaction between these two people about money? - A. No.</p>
               <p>Q. You never heard of his lending the prosecutor any money? - A. No.</p>
               <p>Q. Were they upon any terms together? - A. No further than living in the house together.</p>
               <p>Q. (To the prisoner.) Is there any body here that knows you? - A. No.</p>
               <p>Q. Where is your captain? - A. At Jamaica.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17960113-91-verdict512" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-verdict512" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-verdict512" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. (Aged 18.)(The prisoner was recommended to mercy by the Jury and the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>Tried before Mr. COMMON SERJEANT.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="179601130148"></xptr>Court. (To Mrs. Gomez.) Q. Has he any thing at your house? - A. He has a chest and a large jacket.</p>
               <p>He must have his things. - A. By all means; he came from Portsmouth when he came to me.</p>
               <p>Q. (To Chevrier.) Do you know what ship he belongs to? - A. No.</p>
               <p>Beare. He came over in the Ram.</p>
               <p>Mrs. Gomez. He is a very sober, quiet man.</p>
               <p>Beare. I would undertake to get him a ship, and I dare say he would behave well; he has been very ill, and is ill now; he was examined when he was at the Justice's office, he is very bad, and he said he had pawned the watch to pay the doctor.</p>
               <p>(The Court ordered the Interpreter to inform the prisoner that he had been found guilty, but at the intercession of the prosecutor and the Jury, the Court intended to shew him mercy, and after a <rs id="t17960113-91-punish513" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17960113-91-punish513" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t17960113-91-defend966 t17960113-91-punish513"></join>
               short imprisonment
            </rs>, he would be sent to the hospital to be cured).</p>
